Certainly! Here's an example C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int countOccurrences(std::string filename, std::string word) {
    std::ifstream file(filename);
    std::string line;
    int count = 0;

    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (getline(file, line)) {
            size_t pos = line.find(word);
            while (pos != std::string::npos) {
                count++;
                pos = line.find(word, pos + 1);
            }
        }
        file.close();
    } else {
        std::cerr << "Failed to open the file." << std::endl;
    }

    return count;
}

int main() {
    std::string filename, word;

    std::cout << "Enter the file name: ";
    std::cin >> filename;

    std::cout << "Enter the word to count: ";
    std::cin >> word;

    int occurrences = countOccurrences(filename, word);

    std::cout << word << " occurs " << occurrences << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

To use the program, you need to provide the name of the text file and the word you want to count occurrences for. The program will open the file, read it line by line, and count the number of occurrences of the specified word. It will then display the count to the user.

Note that this program assumes that the text file is in the same directory as the program. If the file is in a different directory, you need to provide the full path to the file.

